---
title: Deconstructed Ratatouille with Garlicky Ciabatta, Feta and Balsamic Tomatoes
description: The definition of deconstructed is ‘to reduce something to its constituent parts’. We’re not sure we agree completely with this- we wouldn’t say there is any reduction going on here. This dish is such a showstopper, that we wanted to let everything from the ratatouille and feta to the garlicky ciabatta, absolutely shine!
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/deconstructed-ratatouille-246eee76-42455be6.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/deconstructed-ratatouille-5af582bc30006c1ae76eeb72-9e1b03c2.pdf
cuisine: French
time required: 30 minutes
course: main course
nutrition:
  calories: 358 kcal
  fat: 14 g
  saturated fat: 8 g
  carbohydrates: 41 g
  sugar: 17 g
  protein: 18 g
  sodium: 2 g
  serving size: 601
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/deconstructed-ratatouille-5af582bc30006c1ae76eeb72
servings: 2
author: Mimi Morley
---

Preheat your oven to 200°C. Halve and peel the @red onion{1}. Chop each half into four pieces. Halve, then remove the core from the @yellow pepper{1} and cut into 1cm wide slices. Halve the @cherry plum tomatoes{200%g}. Remove the stalk top from the @aubergine{1}, cut lengthways into 1cm wide slices, then halve the slices. Remove the top and bottom from the @courgette{1}, halve lengthways and cut each half into four long strips. Next chop those strips into batons roughly the length of your little finger.

Put the onion, pepper and half the tomatoes on a #baking tray{} with a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Sprinkle over the @dried Italian herbs{1%tsp}, drizzle with oil and roast on the top shelf of your oven for ~{20%minutes}. Roughly chop half the @basil{12%leaves}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Put the remaining tomatoes in a #bowl{} with the @balsamic vinegar{1%tbsp}, a drizzle of @olive oil{} and a pinch of salt and pepper. Mix together and leave to the side.

Pop a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil. When hot, add the aubergine slices in one single layer (do them in two batches if you need to). Sprinkle over a pinch of salt and pepper and fry for ~{3-4%minutes} on each side until charred and soft. Once cooked, remove to a #plate{} and cover with #foil{} to keep warm.

Wipe out the pan with #kitchen paper{} and return to medium-high heat (no oil). Season the courgette with salt and pepper. Add to the pan in one single layer and fry until browned all over, turning occasionally, ~{7-8%minutes} (you may need to do these in two batches as well). Remove the courgette from the pan and keep to one side. Cut the @ciabatta{1} in half (as if you were making a sandwich) and leave to the side.

Once the onion, pepper and tomatoes are cooked, take them out of the oven and turn your #grill{} to high. Crumble the @feta cheese{100%g} and sprinkle the chopped basil over the veggies, and stir together (don't worry if the tomatoes break up). Cover with foil to keep warm. Place the ciabatta halves on another baking tray under the grill and toast for ~{2-3%minutes} on each side.

Cut the @garlic clove{1} in half and rub the cut sides across the toasted ciabatta. Drizzle with a little @olive oil{} and season with a pinch of salt and pepper. Put one ciabatta half on each plate, layer on the aubergine slices, then pile on the veggie-feta mixture. Pop the courgettes on top and finish with the balsamic tomatoes. Tear over the remaining basil. Enjoy!